{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"af2b15af-d896-4bd2-9600-596ce2fd64c5","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**.\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the **latest versions** of your installed workloads, matching them to your current SDK. This is exactly what you need after an SDK update, since the old workload versions may be incompatible with the new SDK.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — Re-installs the **same versions** already recorded. It fixes corrupted or partial installs but won't upgrade anything.\n\n**TL;DR:** SDK version changed → `workload update`. Workload files corrupted/missing → `workload repair`.\n\nAfter updating, a `dotnet build` should pick up the compatible MAUI workload.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"571020ff-03bb-49e5-8c26-4aab36a250f3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI workload management — specifically whether to use `dotnet workload update` or `dotnet workload repair` after a SDK update broke their build.\n\nThis is a general .NET knowledge question, not tied to any code in the current directory. I can answer directly.\n\n**`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the latest versions of all installed workloads, matching them to the current SDK version. This is what you want after an SDK update, because the workloads need to be updated to versions compatible with the new SDK.\n\n**`dotnet workload repair`** — Re-installs all currently installed workloads. It doesn't upgrade them — it just reinstalls the same versions. Useful if workload files are corrupted or partially installed.\n\n\nSo `dotnet workload update` is the right move here since the SDK update requires workloads to be synced to compatible versions.","outputTokens":373,"requestId":"A42C:B2E8D:5D0F78D:65834AC:69F0041E"},"id":"13d3ae89-463f-446f-be89-327c6296c470","timestamp":"2026-04-28T00:49:45.333Z","parentId":"dae6f026-afcb-4b27-b102-f6c436d03fdf"}
